{"title_page": "Alexandr Koptsev", "text_new": "'''Alexander Koptsev''' (born 1985) is a Russian-born terrorist. On January 11, 2006, Kopstev burst into [[Bolshaya Bronnaya Synagogue]] in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]] during evening prayers and stabbed eight people with a hunting knife before being wrestled to the ground by the  congregation's leader, [[Rabbi]] Yitzhak Kogan, and his son Yosef Kogan. Four of those injured were in serious condition.<ref name=\":0\" /> On January 13, 2006, Koptsev was charged with racially motivated attempted murder and humiliation of a religious group. He has been described by Russian media as a [[Nazi-Skinheads|racist skinhead]].\n\nAfter the incident, Russia's Chief Rabbi [[Berel Lazar|Berl Lazar]] announced he was cutting short a visit to [[Israel]] to return to Moscow.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4603296.stm|date= 11 January 2006| title=Eight stabbed in Moscow synagogue| publisher=BBC News| accessdate=2006-04-03}}</ref> Lazar stated that the attack was a symptom of a general climate of [[Racism in Russia|intolerance and xenophobia in Russia]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4608742.stm| date=13 January 2006| title=Moscow synagogue suspect charged| publisher=BBC News| accessdate=2006-04-03}}</ref> Rabbi Kogan and his son were later awarded a medal of bravery by [[Vladimir Putin|President Vladimir Putin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lubavitch.com/news/article/2021450/Putin-to-Award-Chabad-Rabbi-For-Bravery.html|title=Chabad Lubavitch Brooklyn New York NY World Headquarters|last=Lubavitch|first=Chabad|website=http://lubavitch.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2006, Koptsev pleaded not guilty of attempting to murder Jewish worshipers at a synagogue. The official charge against him was attempted murder \"motivated by racial hatred\", a charge that is rarely brought in [[Russian courts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Moscow-synagogue-attack:-Supreme-Court-reopens-Koptsev-case-6505.html|title=Moscow synagogue attack: Supreme Court reopens Koptsev case|last=AsiaNews.it|website=asianews.it|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Investigators found [[anti-semitic]] pamphlets in his home, but insist that he was acting alone. He has been diagnosed with a [[Schizophrenia|schizophrenic disorder]], but prosecutors said he was still fit to stand trial.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4758598.stm| date=28 February 2006| title=Moscow synagogue suspect on trial| accessdate=2006-04-03| publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2006, Koptsev was sentenced to 13 years in prison and mandatory psychiatric treatment after being found guilty of attempted murder.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4848910.stm| date=27 March 2006| title=Moscow synagogue attacker jailed| accessdate=2006-04-03| publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Service|first=Haaretz|url=https://www.haaretz.com/1.5317413|title=Russian Prosecutors Charge Moscow Synagogue Attacker With Hate Crimes|date=2006-01-13|work=Haaretz|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Press|first2=The Associated|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2006, Koptsev's lawyer, Vladimir Kirsanov, appealed to Russia's Supreme Court to have his client's sentence reduced, arguing he was mentally unstable, did not kill anyone, and did not cause any disabling injuries. Prosecution lawyers appealed to include the charge of inciting interethnic hatred, which was dropped by the court.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.haaretzdaily.com/hasen/spages/702435.html| date=4 April 2006| title=Report: Moscow synagogue attacker appeals 13-year jail sentence| accessdate=2006-04-04| publisher=Haaretz}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4271783.stm Anti-Semitism alarms Russian Jews] - BBC News, February 17, 2005\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4205597.stm Russian MPs' letter angers Israel] - BBC News, January 25, 2005\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koptsev, Alexander}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian criminals]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Hate crimes]]\n[[Category:Russian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Russia]]\n[[Category:Antisemitic attacks and incidents in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n\n'''Alexander Koptsev''' (born 1985) is a Russian-born terrorist. On January 11, 2006, Kopstev burst into [[Bolshaya Bronnaya Synagogue]] in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]] during evening prayers and stabbed eight people with a hunting knife before being wrestled to the ground by the  congregation's leader, [[Rabbi]] Yitzhak Kogan, and his son Yosef Kogan. Four of those injured were in serious condition. <ref name=\":0\" /> On January 13, 2006, Koptsev was charged with racially motivated attempted murder and humiliation of a religious group. He has been described by Russian media as a [[Nazi-Skinheads|racist skinhead]]. \n\nAfter the incident, Russia's Chief Rabbi [[Berel Lazar|Berl Lazar]] announced he was cutting short a visit to [[Israel]] to return to Moscow.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4603296.stm|date= 11 January 2006| title=Eight stabbed in Moscow synagogue| publisher=BBC News| accessdate=2006-04-03}}</ref> Lazar stated that the attack was a symptom of a general climate of [[Racism in Russia|intolerance and xenophobia in Russia]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4608742.stm| date=13 January 2006| title=Moscow synagogue suspect charged| publisher=BBC News| accessdate=2006-04-03}}</ref> Rabbi Kogan and his son were later awarded a medal of bravery by [[Vladimir Putin|President Vladimir Putin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lubavitch.com/news/article/2021450/Putin-to-Award-Chabad-Rabbi-For-Bravery.html|title=Chabad Lubavitch Brooklyn New York NY World Headquarters|last=Lubavitch|first=Chabad|website=http://lubavitch.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2006, Koptsev pleaded not guilty of attempting to murder Jewish worshipers at a synagogue. The official charge against him was attempted murder \"motivated by racial hatred\", a charge that is rarely brought in [[Russian courts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Moscow-synagogue-attack:-Supreme-Court-reopens-Koptsev-case-6505.html|title=Moscow synagogue attack: Supreme Court reopens Koptsev case|last=AsiaNews.it|website=www.asianews.it|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Investigators found [[anti-semitic]] pamphlets in his home, but insist that he was acting alone. He has been diagnosed with a [[Schizophrenia|schizophrenic disorder]], but prosecutors said he was still fit to stand trial.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4758598.stm| date=28 February 2006| title=Moscow synagogue suspect on trial| accessdate=2006-04-03| publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2006, Koptsev was sentenced to 13 years in prison and mandatory psychiatric treatment after being found guilty of attempted murder.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4848910.stm| date=27 March 2006| title=Moscow synagogue attacker jailed| accessdate=2006-04-03| publisher=BBC News}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Service|first=Haaretz|url=https://www.haaretz.com/1.5317413|title=Russian Prosecutors Charge Moscow Synagogue Attacker With Hate Crimes|date=2006-01-13|work=Haaretz|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Press|first2=The Associated|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2006, Koptsev's lawyer, Vladimir Kirsanov, appealed to Russia's Supreme Court to have his client's sentence reduced, arguing he was mentally unstable, did not kill anyone, and did not cause any disabling injuries. Prosecution lawyers appealed to include the charge of inciting interethnic hatred, which was dropped by the court.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.haaretzdaily.com/hasen/spages/702435.html| date=4 April 2006| title=Report: Moscow synagogue attacker appeals 13-year jail sentence| accessdate=2006-04-04| publisher=Haaretz}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4271783.stm Anti-Semitism alarms Russian Jews] - BBC News, February 17, 2005\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4205597.stm Russian MPs' letter angers Israel] - BBC News, January 25, 2005\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koptsev, Alexander}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian criminals]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Hate crimes]]\n[[Category:Russian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Russia]]\n[[Category:Antisemitic attacks and incidents in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s), replaced: website=www. \u2192 website=", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandr_Koptsev"}
