oneyDew;\"|2.1% ''158''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New York, 1884|1884]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|46.5% ''3,309''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''51.0%''' ''3,627''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.5% ''178''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\nThe County is governed by a fourteen-member [[Board of Supervisors]], composed of the [[town supervisor]] representing each of the ten townships in Seneca County along with four additional at-large members from the towns of [[Waterloo (town), New York|Waterloo]] and [[Seneca Falls (town), New York|Seneca Falls]] (two per township).<ref name=\"CENTRAL\">[http://fingerlakescentral.com/seneca-county-chamber-of-commerce/advocacy/government-directory/ Finger Lakes Central - Seneca County Government], Retrieved May 28, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"BOARD\">[http://www.co.seneca.ny.us/minutes-agendas-laws-resolutions/board-of-supervisors-roster/ Seneca County Board of Supervisors Roster], Retrieved May 28, 2015.</ref> The board normally meets every 2nd Tuesday of the month at the Seneca County Office Building in Waterloo with at least one meeting per year held at the old [[Seneca County Courthouse Complex at Ovid|Seneca County Courthouse Complex]] in Ovid as honor of the two-shire system.<ref name=\"SCHEDULE\">[http://www.co.seneca.ny.us/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/2014_Calendar_BoS1.pdf Seneca County, New York - Board of Supervisors Meeting Schedule], Retrieved May 29, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"OVIDHISTORY\">[http://www.townofovid.org/history2012.html Town of Ovid, New York - History of Ovid], Retrieved May 29, 2015.</ref>  Each supervisor has a weighted vote based on the population of the town they represent.\n\nHistorically a Republican-voting county, Seneca has become more competitive in recent years and is now a swing county in Presidential elections. With the exception of 2000, when Al Gore narrowly carried the county, voters here have opted for the winner of every Presidential election since 1980.\n\n==Communities==\n\n===Towns===\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Covert, New York|Covert]]\n* [[Fayette, New York|Fayette]]\n* [[Junius, New York|Junius]]\n* [[Lodi (town), New York|Lodi]]\n* [[Ovid (town), New York|Ovid]]\n* [[Romulus, New York|Romulus]]\n* [[Seneca Falls (town), New York|Seneca Falls]]\n* [[Tyre, New York|Tyre]]\n* [[Varick, New York|Varick]]\n* [[Waterloo (town), New York|Waterloo]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Villages===\n* [[Interlaken, New York|Interlaken]]\n* [[Lodi (village), New York|Lodi]]\n* [[Ovid (village), New York|Ovid]]\n* [[Waterloo (village), New York|Waterloo]] (county seat)\n\n===Census-designated places===\n* [[Romulus (CDP), New York|Romulus]]\n* [[Seneca Falls (CDP), New York|Seneca Falls]]\n\n===Other hamlets===\nSeneca county has a number of [[Unincorporated community|unincorporated communities]]. Most are considered [[Hamlet (New York)|hamlets]].\n\n* [[Border City, New York|Border City]]\n* Bridgeport\n* [[Canoga, New York|Canoga]]\n* Caywood\n* [[Covert (hamlet), New York|Covert]]\n* Dobbins Corner\n* [[Dublin, New York|Dublin]]\n* [[East Geneva, New York|East Geneva]]\n* [[East Varick, New York|East Varick]]\n* Fayette\n* [[Kendaia]]\n* MacDougall\n* [[Magee, New York|Magee]]\n* Malcom\n* [[Mays Point, New York|Mays Point]]\n* Townsendville\n* [[Tyre (hamlet), New York|Tyre]]\n* [[Varick (hamlet), New York|Varick]]\n* [[Willard, New York|Willard]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|New York (state)}}\n* [[List of counties in New York]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Seneca County, New York]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.co.seneca.ny.us Official Seneca County, New York site]\n* {{curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Counties/Seneca|Seneca County}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050323195236/http://www.usgennet.org/usa/ny/state/his/