u''\n| Peping\n|-\n| [[John Lloyd Cruz]]\n| ''[[ A Second Chance (2015 film) | A Second Chance]]''\n| Engr. Rodolfo \"Popoy\" Gonzales\n|-\n| [[Jericho Rosales]] \n| ''[[Walang Forever]]''\n| Ethan Isaac\n|-\n| [[Dennis Trillo]] \n| ''[[Felix Manalo]]''\n| Felix Manalo\n|-\n| [[Sid Lucero]] \n| ''Apocalypse Child''\n| Ford\n|-\n| Jun Jun Quintana \n| ''Water Lemon''\n| Filemon\n|-\n| [[Luis Alandy]] \n| ''Anino Sa Likod Ng Buwan''\n| Joel\n|-\n| Anthony Falcon\n| ''Anino Sa Likod Ng Buwan''\n| Nando\n|-\n| Francis Guinto\n| ''ARI: My Life With A King''\n| Conrado \"Dado\" Guinto\n|-\n| [[Lou Veloso]] \n| ''Da Dog Show''\n| Sergio\n|-\n| rowspan=8 style=\"text-align:center\" | '''[[40th Gawad Urian Awards|2016]]'''<br /><small>(40th)</small>\n|- style=\"background:#ABCDEF\"\n| '''[[Paolo Ballesteros]]'''\n| '''''[[Die Beautiful]]'''''\n| '''Trisha Echevarria / Patrick'''\n|-\n| [[Tommy Abuel]]\n| ''Dagsin''\n| Justino\n|-\n| Garry Cabalic\n| ''Paglipay''\n| Atan\n|-\n| Ronwaldo Martin\n| ''Pamilya Ordinaryo''\n| Aries\n|-\n| [[Khalil Ramos]]\n| ''[[2 Cool 2 Be 4gotten]]''\n| Felix Salonga\n|-\n| [[Bembol Roco]]\n| ''Pauwi Na''\n| Mang Pepe\n|-\n| [[Pepe Smith]]\n| ''Singing in Graveyards''\n| Pepe The Impersonator\n|-\n| rowspan=11 style=\"text-align:center\" | '''[[41st Gawad Urian Awards|2017]]'''<br /><small>(41st)</small>\n|- style=\"background:#ABCDEF\"\n|'''Abra'''\n|''[[Respeto]]''\n|Hendrix\n|-\n|[[Nonie Buencamino]]\n|''[[Smaller and Smaller Circles (film)|Smaller and Smaller Circles]]''\n|Father Augusto Saenz, [[Society of Jesuits|SJ]]\n|-\n|Timothy Castillo\n|''[[Neomanila]]''\n|Toto\n|-\n|[[Noel Comia Jr.|Noel Comia, Jr.]] \n|''[[Kiko Boksingero]]''\n|\n|-\n|[[Allen Dizon]]\n|''Bomba''\n|\n|-\n|RS Francisco\n|''Bhoy Intsik''\n|\n|-\n|Jojit Lorenzo\n|''[[Changing Partners (film)|Changing Partners]]''\n|Alex\n|-\n|[[Empoy Marquez]]\n|''[[Kita Kita]]''\n|Tonyo\n|-\n|Sandino Martin\n|''[[Changing Partners (film)|Changing Partners]]''\n|Cris\n|-\n|Justine Samson\n|''Balangiga: Howling Wilderness''\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=11 style=\"text-align:center\" | '''[[42nd Gawad Urian Awards|2018]]'''<br /><small>(42nd)</small>\n|- style=\"background:#ABCDEF\"\n|'''[[Eddie Garcia]]'''\n|'''''ML'''''\n|Colonel\n|-\n|[[Carlo Aquino]]\n|''[[Meet Me in St. Gallen]]''\n|Jesse\n|-\n|[[Christian Bables]]\n|''[[Signal Rock]]''\n|Intoy\n|-\n|[[Dingdong Dantes]]\n|[[Sid & Aya: Not a Love Story|Sid & Aya]]\n|Sid\n|-\n|[[Ketchup Eusebio]]\n|''Mamang''\n|Ferdie\n|-\n|[[Eddie Garcia]]\n|''Hintayan ng Langit''\n|Manolo\n|-\n|Miyuki Kamimura\n|''Tanabata\u2019s Wife''\n|\n|-\n|Tony Labrusca\n|''ML''\n|Carlo\n|-\n|Victor Neri\n|''A Short History of a Few Bad Things''\n|Felix Tarongoy\n|-\n|[[Dante Rivero]]\n|''Kung Paano Hinihintay ang Dapithapon''\n|Bene\n|}\n\n==Superlatives==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!width=\"270\"|[[wikt:superlative|Superlative]]\n!colspan=\"2\" width=\"270\"|Best Actor\n|-\n||Actor with most awards\n|[[Phillip Salvador]]<br />[[Richard Gomez]]\n|3\n|-\n|Actor with most nominations\n|[[Christopher de Leon]]\n|13\n|-\n|Oldest Winner\n|[[Eddie Garcia]]\n|90\n|-\n|Oldest Nominee\n|[[Eddie Garcia]]\n|90\n|-\n|Youngest Winner\n|[[Jiro Manio]]\n|12\n|-\n|Youngest Nominee\n|[[Jiro Manio]]\n|12\n|}\n\n==Multiple awards for Best Actor==\n;Three awards \n*[[Richard Gomez]]\n*[[Phillip Salvador]]\n\n;Two awards\n*[[Eddie Garcia]]\n*[[Raymond Bagatsing]]\n*[[Christopher de Leon]]\n*[[Sid Lucero]]\n*[[Vic Silayan]]\n*[[Joel Torre]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gawad Urian}}\n\n[[Category:Film awards for lead actor]]\n[[Category:Philippine film awards]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1976]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMuro-Ami(link changed toMuro-Ami (film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gawad_Urian_for_Best_Actor"}
{"title_page": "Oued Fes", "text_new": "[[File:ETH-BIB-Fluss in F\u00e8s-Nordafrikaflug 1932-LBS MH02-13-0368.tif|thumb|The Oued Bou Khareb (a section of the Oued Fes) flowing through the old [[Medina quarter|medina]] of [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]]. (Photograph from 1932.)|alt=]]\nThe '''Oued Fes''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0641\u0627\u0633|lit=River of Fes}}) is a [[river]] in [[Morocco]]. It is a [[tributary]] of the [[Sebou River]] and historically the main source of water for the city of [[Fez, Morocco|Fes]], after which it is named.\n\nThe river consists of a number of different [[Stream|streams]] which originate in the Sa\u00efss Plain to the south and west of Fes before joining together in the area of [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]], the old city ([[Medina quarter|medina]]) of Fes.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Le Tourneau|first=Roger|title=F\u00e8s avant le protectorat: \u00e9tude \u00e9conomique et sociale d'une ville de l'occident musulman|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Marocaine de Librairie et d'\u00c9dition|year=1949|isbn=|location=Casablanca|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\">{{Cite book|last=M\u00e9talsi|first=Mohamed|title=F\u00e8s: La ville essentielle|publisher=ACR \u00c9dition Internationale|year=2003|isbn=978-2867701528|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> The river runs out of the city eastwards for a short distance before joining the Sebou River. The various branches and sections of the river sometimes have their own names. Over the centuries the river has been split and diverted into a multitude of [[Canal|canals]] that distribute water across the city and once powered a number of historic [[Noria|waterwheels]].<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Source ==\nThe river begins at Ras al-Ma (\"Head of the Water\"), 12 [[Kilometre|kilometres]] southwest of the city, from a hollow of [[Lake|lacustrine]] [[limestone]], with an approximate [[Discharge (hydrology)|flow]] of 500 [[Litre|litres]]/second.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Madani|first=Tariq|date=1999|title=Le r\u00e9seau hydraulique de la ville de F\u00e8s|url=|journal=Arch\u00e9ologie islamique|volume=8-9|pages=119-142|via=}}</ref>{{Rp|131}} \n\n== Oued al-Jawahir ==\n[[File:Oued Fes east of old mechouar (crop).png|left|thumb|View towards the Oued al-Jawahir's exit from under the walls of the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Old Mechouar (Vieux M\u00e9chouar)|Old Mechouar]] (via arched openings seen in the distance), where the first major split into different canals takes place. One of the canals (part of the Oued Fejjalin division) is seen on the left.|alt=]]\nThe main branch of the river, skirts the northern edge of the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)|Royal Palace]] (''Dar al-Makhzen'') grounds and of [[Fes Jdid|Fes el-Jdid]] before entering Fes el-Bali. This section is also known as known also as the ''Oued al-Jawahir'' ({{Lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0648\u0627\u0647\u0631|lit=River of Pearls}}).<ref name=\":02\" /> It once passed through a flat area of marshes and swamps located near what is now Fes el-Jdid and the modern ''Ville Nouvelle'', before emerging at a number places.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Gaudio|first=Attilio|title=F\u00e8s: Joyau de la civilisation islamique|publisher=Les Presse de l'UNESCO: Nouvelles \u00c9ditions Latines|year=1982|isbn=2723301591|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> However, since the founding of Fes el-Jdid, the Oued al-Jawahir was progressively diverted and many of its old streams seem to have disappeared.<ref name=\":6\" /> The river's flow was re-engineered to provide water for the Royal Palace complex and a succession of royal gardens such as the Mosara Gardens of the [[Marinid Sultanate|Marinids]] (now disappeared) and the 19th-century [[Jnan Sbil Gardens]] (still extant).<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> Fes el-Bali's extensive water network is much older and its current outlines were begun by the [[Zenata]] [[emir]] Dounas ibn Hamama between 1137 and 1049, and then further elaborate by the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravid]] emir [[Yusuf ibn Tashfin|Yusuf ib Tashfin]] between 1069 (the Almoravid conquest of Fes) and 1106.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Marcos Cobaleda|first=Maria|last2=Villalba Sola|first2=Dolores|date=2018|title=Transformations in medieval Fez: Almoravid\nhydraulic system and changes in the Almohad\nwalls|url=|journal=The Journal of North African Studies|volume=23 (4)|pages=591-623|via=}}</ref> \n\nFlowing eastwards, the Oued al-Jawahir passes through the [[Dar al-Makina]] and beneath the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Old Mechouar (Vieux M\u00e9chouar)|Vieux Mechouar]] (Old Mechouar) near [[Bab Dekkakin]] before reemerging on its eastern side. Here it emerges from four arched openings at ground level, where the first major divisions of the river take place, feeding a number of canals (many of them hidden under houses and streets) through Fes el-Bali which eventually spill back into the Oued Bou Khareb (the name of the main river inside the city).<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> There are four main historic canal divisions: the ''Oued Fejjalin'', the ''Oued el-Hamiya'', the ''Sakiyat el-Abbasa'', and the ''Oued Shrashar''.<ref name=\":02\" /> Each of these is then further subdivided. The Oued Fejjalin is one of the most important, and from it the ''Oued el-Lemtiyyin'' also splits off to supply the northernmost parts of the city.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> The Oued el-Lemtiyyin passes under the Bou Jeloud area and initially travels under the houses of Tala'a Kebira street until it reaches the Bou Inania Madrasa. Here, just east of the madrasa, the water is collected by a distribution structure with three arched or vaulted tunnels which split the water into three more canals.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> The Oued el-Hamiya splits from the Fejjalin branch at Jnan Sbil before dividing into more branches which mostly supply the southern parts of the city, with one branch also supplying, via an aqueduct, the [[Andalusian Mosque|Andalus]] quarter on the opposite shore of the Bou Khareb river.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The Sakiyat al-Abbasa and the Oued Shrashar supplied gardens between Fes el-Jdid and Fes el-Bali.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nMany of these canals are now underground, with only some ancient [[Toponymy|toponyms]] hinting at former bridges that passed over them (e.g. the name ''Qantrat Bou Rous'' in the western part of [[Tala'a Kebira]]).<ref name=\":02\" /> These canals and streams also feed a number of industries such as the historic [[Tanning (leather)|tanneries]] of the city, the most famous of which are the [[Chouara Tannery|Chouara Tanneries]].<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Oued Bou Khareb ==\n[[File:Oued Bou Khareb.jpg|thumb|Oued Bou Khareb (in 2010).]]\n''Oued Bou Khareb'' (or sometimes ''Oued el-Kbir'') is the usual name given to the main urban course of the river.<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|122}} This branch is fed by the various canals that split off from the Oued al-Jawahir to supply the city before spilling into this ravine, such that it acted as a collector for the city's used water. The Oued Bou Khareb is also fed by two other rivers or streams that enter the city from the south (at Bab Jdid), called the ''Oued ez-Zitoun'' and the ''Oued Bou Fekran''.<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|234}} These two rivers also fed another important canal, called ''Oued Masmuda'', which supplied water for the Andalus quarter of Fes, on the southeast side of the Bou Khareb river.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The Masmuda canal passed through the old walls of the city through an opening called ''Bab ash-Shobbak'' (\"Gate of the Window\") which was guarded by an iron [[grille]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> \n\nThe course of the Bou Khareb is the lowest point in the medina of Fes el-Bali and also forms the historical boundary between the [[University of al-Qarawiyyin|Qarawiyyin]] and [[Andalusian Mosque|Andalus]] quarters of the city, which were originally two separate cities (''al-'Aliya'' and ''Madinat Fas'') in their early history before being joined together by the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravids]] in the 11th century.<ref name=\":02\" /> Much of the Oued Bou Khareb's course, between Bab Jdid and [[R'cif Mosque|Place R'cif]], is now hidden beneath a modern road for car traffic (one of the few that penetrates the medina). The road covers the river up to Place R'cif, a large square at the heart of the medina, and the river reemerges on the north side of square.<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> From there the river runs northeast and exits the city between [[Bab Guissa]] and the former gate of Bab Sidi Bou Jida.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Historic Bridges ==\n[[File:ETH-BIB-Br\u00fccke in F\u00e8s-Nordafrikaflug 1932-LBS MH02-13-0385.tif|thumb|The Terrafin Bridge (\"Bridge of the Cobblers\") over the river in 1932. Today the bridge is located at the northern edge of Place R'cif.]]\nThe Oued Bou Khareb is crossed by several historic bridges, some of which are believed to date from before the unification of the two shores into a single city in the 11th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://visitefes.com/la-magnifique-renovation-des-27-monuments-de-fes/|title=La magnifique r\u00e9novation des 27 monuments de F\u00e8s \u2013 Conseil R\u00e9gional du Tourisme (CRT) de F\u00e8s|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The ''Qantra Bin el-Moudoun'' (\"Bridge Between the Two Cities\") was the northernmost of them, followed to the south by the ''Qantrat Sebbaghin'' (\"Bridge of the Tanners\") and by the ''Qantrat Terrafin'' (\"Bridge of the Cobblers\") just north of Place R'cif. Another bridge, the Bridge of Sidi al-'Awwad, was located further south but disappeared during the 20th century when the river was covered by the modern paved road.<ref name=\":02\" />  The Sebbaghin Bridge, also known as the Khrashfiyin Bridge (or ''Khrachfiyine'' in the [[French language|French]] [[transliteration]]), is believed to have been originally built by the [[Zenata]] [[emir]] Dounas ibn Hamama in the early 11th century and restored for the last time by the Marinids in the 14th century.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first Terrafin and Bin el-Moudoun bridges are also believed to date from the same time the 11th century,<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> though other scholarly sources attribute the current bridges to the Almoravid era (late 11th to early 12th centuries) when the two early cities of Fes were unified.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Terrafin Bridge (originally named Qantrat Bab al-Silsila) is also notable for having been lined with shops on both sides.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Pollution problems and rehabilitation efforts ==\n[[File:Fes, Old city.jpg|thumb|Traditional [[Tanning (leather)|tanners]] are seen working along the Oued Bou Khareb (2006; before recent renovations to the area).|alt=|left]]\n{{multiple image\n | width = 220\n | direction = vertical\n | image1 = Fes bridge restoration 1.jpg\n | image2 = Fes bridge restoration 3.jpg\n | footer = The Sebbaghin or Khrashfiyin Bridge at the beginning of restoration (November 2014) and after restoration (2015).\n}}\nThe river, particularly the Oued Bou Khareb within the old medina, had long suffered from heavy pollution due to sewage, the activities of the nearby tanneries (which generate chemical waste), and to being used as a dumping ground by residents.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcitiesdive.com/ex/sustainablecitiescollective/revitalization-fez-river-reclaimed-public-space/171636/|title=Revitalization of the Fez River: A Reclaimed Public Space {{!}} Smart Cities Dive|website=www.smartcitiesdive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.morocco.com/blog/the-rejuvenation-of-the-fez-river/|title=Morocco.com {{!}} The Rejuvenation of the Fez River|website=www.morocco.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Even the name Oued Bou Khareb meant \"River of Trash\".<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In recent times the city authorities had begun covering the exposed parts of the river with concrete slabs, which only led to more garbage piling up.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn the late 2000s, a large-scale project to rehabilitate the river system and its urban environment was begun. The project, led by architect [[Aziza Chaouni]], included the cleaning up of the river, the renovation of its urban shoreline, the creation of open pedestrian walkways, and renovation of existing open spaces along the river such Place R'cif and Place Lalla Yeddouna.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daniels.utoronto.ca/news/2014/03/20/aziza-chaouni-presents-2014-ted-talk-her-efforts-uncover-fez-river-morocco|title=Aziza Chaouni presents a 2014 TED Talk on her efforts to uncover the Fez River in Morocco|date=2014-03-20|website=Daniels|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The proposal to improve water quality the proposal also included the creation of wetlands (which had previously existed along the river's course) and the restoration of the river's canals.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe rehabilitation of the river, which has since been underway, also took place alongside broader efforts to restore the historical monuments and landmarks of the old city, mostly under the direction of the local heritage restoration agency ADER-Fes. This included the restoration of the bridges over the Bou Khareb river, with the Terrafin and Sebbaghin/Khrashfiyin bridges being restored in the 2010s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Morocco]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:ETH-BIB-Fluss in F\u00e8s-Nordafrikaflug 1932-LBS MH02-13-0368.tif|thumb|The Oued Bou Khareb (a section of the Oued Fes) flowing through the old [[Medina quarter|medina]] of [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]]. (Photograph from 1932.)|alt=]]\nThe '''Oued Fes''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0641\u0627\u0633|lit=River of Fes}}) is a [[river]] in [[Morocco]]. It is a [[tributary]] of the [[Sebou River]] and historically the main source of water for the city of [[Fez, Morocco|Fes]], after which it is named.\n\nThe river consists of a number of different [[Stream|streams]] which originate in the Sa\u00efss Plain to the south and west of Fes before joining together in the area of [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]], the old city ([[Medina quarter|medina]]) of Fes.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Le Tourneau|first=Roger|title=F\u00e8s avant le protectorat: \u00e9tude \u00e9conomique et sociale d'une ville de l'occident musulman|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Marocaine de Librairie et d'\u00c9dition|year=1949|isbn=|location=Casablanca|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\">{{Cite book|last=M\u00e9talsi|first=Mohamed|title=F\u00e8s: La ville essentielle|publisher=ACR \u00c9dition Internationale|year=2003|isbn=978-2867701528|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> The river runs out of the city eastwards for a short distance before joining the Sebou River. The various branches and sections of the river sometimes have their own names. Over the centuries the river has been split and diverted into a multitude of [[Canal|canals]] that distribute water across the city and once powered a number of historic [[Noria|waterwheels]].<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Source ==\nThe river begins at Ras al-Ma (\"Head of the Water\"), 12 [[Kilometre|kilometres]] southwest of the city, from a hollow of [[Lake|lacustrine]] [[limestone]], with an approximate [[Discharge (hydrology)|flow]] of 500 [[Litre|litres]]/second.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Madani|first=Tariq|date=1999|title=Le r\u00e9seau hydraulique de la ville de F\u00e8s|url=|journal=Arch\u00e9ologie islamique|volume=8-9|pages=119-142|via=}}</ref>{{Rp|131}} \n\n== Oued al-Jawahir ==\n[[File:Oued Fes east of old mechouar (crop).png|left|thumb|View towards the Oued al-Jawahir's exit from under the walls of the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Old Mechouar (Vieux M\u00e9chouar)|Old Mechouar]] (via arched openings seen in the distance), where the first major split into different canals takes place. One of the canals (part of the Oued Fejjalin division) is seen on the left.|alt=]]\nThe main branch of the river, skirts the northern edge of the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)|Royal Palace]] (''Dar al-Makhzen'') grounds and of [[Fes Jdid|Fes el-Jdid]] before entering Fes el-Bali. This section is also known as known also as the ''Oued al-Jawahir'' ({{Lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0648\u0627\u0647\u0631|lit=River of Pearls}}).<ref name=\":02\" /> It once passed through a flat area of marshes and swamps located near what is now Fes el-Jdid and the modern ''Ville Nouvelle'', before emerging at a number places.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Gaudio|first=Attilio|title=F\u00e8s: Joyau de la civilisation islamique|publisher=Les Presse de l'UNESCO: Nouvelles \u00c9ditions Latines|year=1982|isbn=2723301591|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> However, since the founding of Fes el-Jdid, the Oued al-Jawahir was progressively diverted and many of its old streams seem to have disappeared.<ref name=\":6\" /> The river's flow was re-engineered to provide water for the Royal Palace complex and a succession of royal gardens such as the Mosara Gardens of the [[Marinid Sultanate|Marinids]] (now disappeared) and the 19th-century [[Jnan Sbil Gardens]] (still extant).<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> Fes el-Bali's extensive water network is much older and its current outlines were begun by the [[Zenata]] [[emir]] Dounas ibn Hamama between 1137 and 1049, and then further elaborate by the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravid]] emir [[Yusuf ibn Tashfin|Yusuf ib Tashfin]] between 1069 (the Almoravid conquest of Fes) and 1106.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Marcos Cobaleda|first=Maria|last2=Villalba Sola|first2=Dolores|date=2018|title=Transformations in medieval Fez: Almoravid\nhydraulic system and changes in the Almohad\nwalls|url=|journal=The Journal of North African Studies|volume=23 (4)|pages=591-623|via=}}</ref> \n\nFlowing eastwards, the Oued al-Jawahir passes through the [[Dar al-Makina]] and beneath the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Old Mechouar (Vieux M\u00e9chouar)|Vieux Mechouar]] (Old Mechouar) near [[Bab Dekkakin]] before reemerging on its eastern side. Here it emerges from four arched openings at ground level, where the first major divisions of the river take place, feeding a number of canals (many of them hidden under houses and streets) through Fes el-Bali which eventually spill back into the Oued Bou Khareb (the name of the main river inside the city).<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> There are four main historic canal divisions: the ''Oued Fejjalin'', the ''Oued el-Hamiya'', the ''Sakiyat el-Abbasa'', and the ''Oued Shrashar''.<ref name=\":02\" /> Each of these is then further subdivided. The Oued Fejjalin is one of the most important, and from it the ''Oued el-Lemtiyyin'' also splits off to supply the northernmost parts of the city.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> The Oued el-Lemtiyyin passes under the Bou Jeloud area and initially travels under the houses of Tala'a Kebira street until it reaches the Bou Inania Madrasa. Here, just east of the madrasa, the water is collected by a distribution structure with three arched or vaulted tunnels which split the water into three more canals.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> The Oued el-Hamiya splits from the Fejjalin branch at Jnan Sbil before dividing into more branches which mostly supply the southern parts of the city, with one branch also supplying, via an aqueduct, the [[Andalusian Mosque|Andalus]] quarter on the opposite shore of the Bou Khareb river.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The Sakiyat al-Abbasa and the Oued Shrashar supplied gardens between Fes el-Jdid and Fes el-Bali.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nMany of these canals are now underground, with only some ancient [[Toponymy|toponyms]] hinting at former bridges that passed over them (e.g. the name ''Qantrat Bou Rous'' in the western part of [[Tala'a Kebira]]).<ref name=\":02\" /> These canals and streams also feed a number of industries such as the historic [[Tanning (leather)|tanneries]] of the city, the most famous of which are the [[Chouara Tannery|Chouara Tanneries]].<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Oued Bou Khareb ==\n[[File:Oued Bou Khareb.jpg|thumb|Oued Bou Khareb (in 2010).]]\n''Oued Bou Khareb'' (or sometimes ''Oued el-Kbir'') is the usual name given to the main urban course of the river.<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|122}} This branch is fed by the various canals that split off from the Oued al-Jawahir to supply the city before spilling into this ravine, such that it acted as a collector for the city's used water. The Oued Bou Khareb is also fed by two other rivers or streams that enter the city from the south (at Bab Jdid), called the ''Oued ez-Zitoun'' and the ''Oued Bou Fekran''.<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|234}} These two rivers also fed another important canal, called ''Oued Masmuda'', which supplied water for the Andalus quarter of Fes, on the southeast side of the Bou Khareb river.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The Masmuda canal passed through the old walls of the city through an opening called ''Bab ash-Shobbak'' (\"Gate of the Window\") which was guarded by an iron [[grille]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> \n\nThe course of the Bou Khareb is the lowest point in the medina of Fes el-Bali and also forms the historical boundary between the [[University of al-Qarawiyyin|Qarawiyyin]] and [[Andalusian Mosque|Andalus]] quarters of the city, which were originally two separate cities (''al-'Aliya'' and ''Madinat Fas'') in their early history before being joined together by the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravids]] in the 11th century.<ref name=\":02\" /> Much of the Oued Bou Khareb's course, between Bab Jdid and [[R'cif Mosque|Place R'cif]], is now hidden beneath a modern road for car traffic (one of the few that penetrates the medina). The road covers the river up to Place R'cif, a large square at the heart of the medina, and the river reemerges on the north side of square.<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> From there the river runs northeast and exits the city between [[Bab Guissa]] and the former gate of Bab Sidi Bou Jida.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Historic Bridges ==\n[[File:ETH-BIB-Br\u00fccke in F\u00e8s-Nordafrikaflug 1932-LBS MH02-13-0385.tif|thumb|The Terrafin Bridge (\"Bridge of the Cobblers\") over the river in 1932. Today the bridge is located at the northern edge of Place R'cif.]]\nThe Oued Bou Khareb is crossed by several historic bridges, some of which are believed to date from before the unification of the two shores into a single city in the 11th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://visitefes.com/la-magnifique-renovation-des-27-monuments-de-fes/|title=La magnifique r\u00e9novation des 27 monuments de F\u00e8s \u2013 Conseil R\u00e9gional du Tourisme (CRT) de F\u00e8s|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The ''Qantra Bin el-Moudoun'' (\"Bridge Between the Two Cities\") was the northernmost of them, followed to the south by the ''Qantrat Sebbaghin'' (\"Bridge of the Tanners\") and by the ''Qantrat Terrafin'' (\"Bridge of the Cobblers\") just north of Place R'cif. Another bridge, the Bridge of Sidi al-'Awwad, was located further south but disappeared during the 20th century when the river was covered by the modern paved road.<ref name=\":02\" />  The Sebbaghin Bridge, also known as the Khrashfiyin Bridge (or ''Khrachfiyine'' in the [[French language|French]] [[transliteration]]), is believed to have been originally built by the [[Zenata]] [[emir]] Dounas ibn Hamama in the early 11th century and restored for the last time by the Marinids in the 14th century.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first Terrafin and Bin el-Moudoun bridges are are also believed to date from the same time the 11th century,<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> though other scholarly sources attribute the current bridges to the Almoravid era (late 11th to early 12th centuries) when the two early cities of Fes were unified.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Terrafin Bridge (originally named Qantrat Bab al-Silsila) is also notable for having been lined with shops on both sides.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Pollution problems and rehabilitation efforts ==\n[[File:Fes, Old city.jpg|thumb|Traditional [[Tanning (leather)|tanners]] are seen working along the Oued Bou Khareb (2006; before recent renovations to the area).|alt=|left]]\n{{multiple image\n | width = 220\n | direction = vertical\n | image1 = Fes bridge restoration 1.jpg\n | image2 = Fes bridge restoration 3.jpg\n | footer = The Sebbaghin or Khrashfiyin Bridge at the beginning of restoration (November 2014) and after restoration (2015).\n}}\nThe river, particularly the Oued Bou Khareb within the old medina, had long suffered from heavy pollution due to sewage, the activities of the nearby tanneries (which generate chemical waste), and to being used as a dumping ground by residents.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcitiesdive.com/ex/sustainablecitiescollective/revitalization-fez-river-reclaimed-public-space/171636/|title=Revitalization of the Fez River: A Reclaimed Public Space {{!}} Smart Cities Dive|website=www.smartcitiesdive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.morocco.com/blog/the-rejuvenation-of-the-fez-river/|title=Morocco.com {{!}} The Rejuvenation of the Fez River|website=www.morocco.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Even the name Oued Bou Khareb meant \"River of Trash\".<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In recent times the city authorities had begun covering the exposed parts of the river with concrete slabs, which only led to more garbage piling up.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn the late 2000s, a large-scale project to rehabilitate the river system and its urban environment was begun. The project, led by architect [[Aziza Chaouni]], included the cleaning up of the river, the renovation of its urban shoreline, the creation of open pedestrian walkways, and renovation of existing open spaces along the river such Place R'cif and Place Lalla Yeddouna.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daniels.utoronto.ca/news/2014/03/20/aziza-chaouni-presents-2014-ted-talk-her-efforts-uncover-fez-river-morocco|title=Aziza Chaouni presents a 2014 TED Talk on her efforts to uncover the Fez River in Morocco|date=2014-03-20|website=Daniels|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The proposal to improve water quality the proposal also included the creation of wetlands (which had previously existed along the river's course) and the restoration of the river's canals.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe rehabilitation of the river, which has since been underway, also took place alongside broader efforts to restore the historical monuments and landmarks of the old city, mostly under the direction of the local heritage restoration agency ADER-Fes. This included the restoration of the bridges over the Bou Khareb river, with the Terrafin and Sebbaghin/Khrashfiyin bridges being restored in the 2010s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Morocco]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oued_Fes"}
{"title_page": "Metro Manila Film Festival Award for Best Screenplay", "text_new": "{{main|Metro Manila Film Festival}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name           = [[Metro Manila Film Festival|Metro Manila Film Festival Award]] for Best Screenplay\n| description    = Best Script/Writing\n| presenter      = [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority|MMDA]]\n| country        = [[Philippines]]\n| year           = 1975\n| holder         =Crisanto B. Aquino, ''Write About Love'' ([[2019 Metro Manila Film Festival|2019]])\n| website        = {{url|http://www.mmda.gov.ph/mmff/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Metro Manila Film Festival Award for Best Screenplay''' is an award presented annually by the [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] (MMDA). It was first awarded at the [[1975 Metro Manila Film Festival|1st Metro Manila Film Festival]] ceremony, held in 1975; Luciano Carlos received the award for his script in ''Batu-Bato sa Langit'' and it is given in honor of a scriptwriter with best [[screenplay|script]] while working within the [[film industry]].<ref name=\"MMFF1\">[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1975 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1975\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref> Currently, nominees and winners are determined by Executive Committees, headed by the [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] Chairman and key members of the film industry.<ref>[http://www.mmda.gov.ph/mmff/ \"Official website\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005130322/http://www.mmda.gov.ph/mmff/ |date=2012-10-05 }}. ''MMDA''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n\n{|id=\"toc\" class=\"toc plainlinks\" style= summary=\"Metro Manila Film Festival Award for Best Screenwriter\"\n|-\n! Contents: __NOTOC__\n|\n'''[[#1970s|1970s]]'''{{\u00b7}}'''[[#1980s|1980s]]'''{{\u00b7}}'''[[#1990s|1990s]]'''{{\u00b7}}'''[[#2000s|2000s]]'''{{\u00b7}}'''[[#2010s|2010s]]'''{{\u00b7}}'''[[#2020s|2020s]]'''<br>\n[[#Multiple awards for Best Screenplay|Multiple awards]]{{\u00b7}}[[#Notes|Notes]]{{\u00b7}}[[#References|References]]{{\u00b7}}[[#External links|External links]]\n|}\n\n==Winners and nominees==\n===1970s===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" background: #f6e39c;\n|- style=\"background:#bebebe;\"\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:8%;\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40%;\"| Film\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:50%;\"| Screenwriter(s)\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2%;\"|Ref\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |1975 <br /><small>[[1975 Metro Manila Film Festival|(1st)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''Batu-Bato sa Langit''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Luciano Carlos\n|<ref name=\"MMFF1\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |1976 <br /><small>[[1976 Metro Manila Film Festival|(2nd)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Ganito Kami Noon, Paano Kayo Ngayon]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Eddie Romero]] & [[Roy Iglesias]]\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1976 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1976\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |1977 <br /><small>[[1977 Metro Manila Film Festival|(3rd)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''Burlesk Queen''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Mauro Gia Samonte\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1977 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1977\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |1978 <br /><small>[[1978 Metro Manila Film Festival|(4th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''Rubia Servios''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Mario O'Hara]]\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1978 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1978\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |1979 <br /><small>[[1979 Metro Manila Film Festival|(5th)]] </small>\n|colspan=2|''None''<ref group=\"Note\" name =\"i\">No \"Best Screenplay\" announced.</ref> \n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1979 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1979\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|}\n\n===1980s===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" background: #f6e39c;\n|- style=\"background:#bebebe;\"\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:8%;\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40%;\"| Film\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:50%;\"| Screenwriter(s)\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2%;\"|Ref\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|1980 <br /><small>[[1980 Metro Manila Film Festival|(6th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''Taga sa Panahon''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Jose N. Carreon\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1980 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1980\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |1981 <br /><small>[[1981 Metro Manila Film Festival|(7th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Kisapmata]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Clodualdo del Mundo, Jr.]], Raquel Villavicencio, and [[Mike De Leon]]\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1981 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1981\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|1982 <br /><small>[[1982 Metro Manila Film Festival|(8th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''Moral''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Ricky Lee]]\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1982 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1982\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |1983 <br /><small>[[1983 Metro Manila Film Festival|(9th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |'' Bago Kumalat ang Kamandag''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Willy Milan and Ronnie Paredes\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1983 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1983\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|1984 <br /><small>[[1984 Metro Manila Film Festival|(10th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background: