gn:center\"|2005 <br /><small>[[2005 Metro Manila Film Festival|(31st)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Blue Moon (2006 film)|Blue Moon]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Allan Tijamo\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2005 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2005\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2006 <br /><small>[[2006 Metro Manila Film Festival|(32nd)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\"|''[[Kasal, Kasali, Kasalo]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Jose Javier Reyes]]\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2006 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2006\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2007 <br /><small>[[2007 Metro Manila Film Festival|(33rd)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''Katas ng Saudi''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Jose Javier Reyes]]\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2007 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2007\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |2008 <br /><small>[[2008 Metro Manila Film Festival|(34th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Baler (film)|Baler]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Roy Iglesias]]\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2008 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2008\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |2009 <br /><small>[[2009 Metro Manila Film Festival|(35th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Mano Po 6: A Mother's Love]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" | [[Roy Iglesias]]\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2009 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2009\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|}\n\n===2010s===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" background: #f6e39c;\n|- style=\"background:#bebebe;\"\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:8%;\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40%;\"| Film\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:50%;\"| Screenwriter(s)\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2%;\"|Ref\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2010 <br /><small>[[2010 Metro Manila Film Festival|(36th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Ang Tanging Ina Mo (Last na 'To!)]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" | Mel del Rosario\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2010 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2010\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2011 <br /><small>[[2011 Metro Manila Film Festival|(37th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Manila Kingpin: The Asiong Salonga Story]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Roy Iglesias]]\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2011 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2011\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2012 <br /><small>[[2012 Metro Manila Film Festival|(38th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[One More Try (film)|One More Try]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" | Anna Karenina and Jay Gazmin\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2012 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2012\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2013 <br /><small>[[2013 Metro Manila Film Festival|(39th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[10,000 Hours (film)|10,000 Hours]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" | Ryllah Epifania Berico and Keiko Aquino\n|<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2013 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2013\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2014 <br /><small>[[2014 Metro Manila Film Festival|(40th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[English Only, Please]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" | [[Antoinette Jadaone]] and Anj Pessumal\n|<ref>[http://www.rappler.com/entertainment/news/79103-full-list-winners-metro-manila-film-festival-mmff-2014 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:2014\"]. ''Rappler''. Retrieved 2014-12-28.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" rowspan=3|2015 <br /><small>[[2015 Metro Manila Film Festival|(41st)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Walang Forever|#Walang Forever]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" | Paul Sta. Ana\n|rowspan=3|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Chuck|title=Winners: 2015 Metro Manila Film Festival awards night|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2015/12/28/1536999/list-winners-2015-metro-manila-film-festival-awards-night|website=Philippine Star|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Honor Thy Father]]''||Michiko Yamamoto\n|-\n| ''[[My Bebe Love|My Bebe Love: #KiligPaMore]]''||[[Jose Javier Reyes]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2016 <br /><small>[[2016 Metro Manila Film Festival|(42nd)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Seklusyon]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Anton C. Santamaria\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Winners at MMFF\u2019s Gabi Ng Parangal night|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/594086/lifestyle/artandculture/winners-at-mmff-s-gabi-ng-parangal |work=[[GMA News]] |date=29 December 2016 |accessdate=29 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2017 <br /><small>[[2017 Metro Manila Film Festival|(43rd)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[All of You (film)|All of You]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Carl Chavez, [[Dan Villegas]] and Mae Chua\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/life-and-style/specials/mmff/192303-winners-mmff-2017-awards-night-gabi-ng-parangal|title=FULL LIST: Winners of the MMFF 2017 Gabi ng Parangal|last=|first=|date=December 27, 2017|website=Rappler|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|2018 <br /><small>[[2018 Metro Manila Film Festival|(44th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Rainbow's Sunset]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Eric Ramos\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/entertainment/news/219710-winners-mmff-2018-awards-night-gabi-ng-parangal|title=FULL LIST: Winners, MMFF 2018 Gabi ng Parangal|last=|first=|date=December 27, 2018|website=Rappler|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" rowspan=3 |2019 <br /><small>[[2019 Metro Manila Film Festival|(45th)]] </small>\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Write About Love (film)|Write About Love]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Crisanto B. Aquino\n| rowspan=3| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2019/12/27/1980258/full-list-mmff-2019-winners|title=FULL LIST: MMFF 2019 winners|last=|first=|date=December 27, 2019|website=Philippine Star|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Mindanao (film)|Mindanao]]'' || Honee Alipio \n|-\n| ''Sunod'' || Anton Santamaria \n|}\n\n===2020s===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" background: #f6e39c;\n|- style=\"background:#bebebe;\"\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:8%;\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40%;\"| Film\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:50%;\"| Screenwriter(s)\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2%;\"|Ref\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==Multiple awards for Best Screenplay==\nThroughout the history of [[Metro Manila Film Festival]] (MMFF), there have been scriptwriters who received multiple Awards for Best Screenplay. As of 2015 (41st MMFF), 4 scriptwriters have received two or more Best Screenplay awards.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"width:55%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Scriptwriter!! Record Set!! First year awarded!!Recent year awarded\n|-\n|[[Roy Iglesias]]||rowspan=2|8||[[1976 Metro Manila Film Festival|1976]]||[[2011 Metro Manila Film Festival|2011]]\n|-\n|[[Ricky Lee]]||[[1982 Metro Manila Film Festival|1982]]||[[1999 Metro Manila Film Festival|1999]]\n|-\n|[[Jose Javier Reyes]]||3||[[1993 Metro Manila Film Festival|1993]]||[[2007 Metro Manila Film Festival|2007]]\n|-\n|[[Jun Lana]]||2||[[1998 Metro Manila Film Festival|1998]]||[[1999 Metro Manila Film Festival|1999]]\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"Note\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/Sections/Awards/Metro_Manila_Film_Festival/ IMDB: Metro Manila Film Festival]\n*[http://mmda.gov.ph/mmff/ Official website of the Metro Manila Film Festival]\n\n{{MMFF}}\n\n[[Category:Metro Manila Film Festival]]\n[[Category:Philippine film awards]]\n\n[[nl:Metro Manila Film Festival]]\n[[tl:Paligsahan ng mga Pelikula ng Kalakhang Maynila]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMuro-Ami(link changed toMuro-Ami (film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metro_Manila_Film_Festival_Award_for_Best_Screenplay"}
{"title_page": "Lluest-wen Reservoir", "text_new": "{{short description|Reservoir in the borough of Rhondda Cynon Taf, South Wales}}\n{{Infobox lake\n | name = Lluest-wen Reservoir\n | image = Lluest-wen Reservoir - geograph.org.uk - 1017788.jpg\n | caption = \n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Rhondda|Rhondda Fach Valley]], [[South Wales Valleys]], Wales\n | coords = {{coord|51.705|-3.525|type:waterbody_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n | type = [[reservoir]]\n | inflow = \n | outflow = \n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United Kingdom\n | length = \n | width = \n | area = \n | depth = \n | max-depth = \n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = \n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n'''Lluest-wen Reservoir''' (Welsh: ''Cronfa-ddwr Lluest-wen'') is a [[reservoir]] at the top of the [[Rhondda|Rhondda Fach Valley]] (Welsh: ''Cwm Rhondda Fach''), in the borough of [[Rhondda Cynon Taf]], South Wales. Parts of it fall within the [[Community (Wales)|communities]] of [[Rhigos]], [[Aberdare]] and [[Treherbert]]. A recreational walking route, the [[Coed Morgannwg Way]], and route 47 of the [[National Cycle Network]] run northeast and southwest of it respectively.<ref>Ordnance Survey 1:25,000 scale Explorer map sheet 166 ''Rhondda & Merthyr Tydfil/Merthyr Tudful''</ref>\n\nThe reservoir gained national attention in 1969 when significant damage was discovered that led to the evacuation of hundreds of nearby homes and prompted more than \u00a31 million of emergency repair works. \n\n==Geography and construction==\nThe reservoir was built in 1898 and covers an area of {{convert|20|acre}}.<ref name=\"wo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/40-years-rhondda-fach-nearly-1940564 |title=40 years since Rhondda Fach nearly flooded |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=21 January 2010 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> It was located at the top of the [[Rhondda Fach]], near the village of [[Maerdy]]. The site holds around {{convert|242000000|impgal}} of water.<ref name=\"wo\"/> The dam was built using earth embankments, the core of which were constructed of clay.<ref name=\"hans\">{{cite web |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1970/jan/19/wales-Lluest-wen-Reservoir |title=Wales (Lluest-Wen Reservoir) |publisher=Hansard |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ice\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.icevirtuallibrary.com/doi/full/10.1680/jdare.18.00038 |title=Lluest Wen: the near failure and subsequent repair of a Pennine type dam |journal=Dams and Reservoirs |last1=Ackers |first1=John |last2=Pether |first2=Rachel |last3=Warren |first3=Alan |pp=119\u2013122 |issue=3 |date=September 2018 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |via=Institute of Civil Engineers Virtual Library}}</ref> The banks were reinforced during the early 1970s with {{convert|600|mm|adj=on}} thick concrete.<ref name=\"ice\"/>\n\n==History==\nConstruction of the reservoir was completed in 1898. In its formative years, there were several incidents of the reservoir suffering damage. Two minor leaks in the embankments were fixed during the first decade. A larger leak was filled in with around 40 wheelbarrows of rubble in December 1910 and required refilling a year later. Settling issues caused further issues in the 1910s and rerouting work was undertaken when it was discovered that the top of the core in the embankments was only {{convert|2|ft|spell=in}} above the water level. In April 1917, a local official recommended that the reservoir be drained or the water level significantly lowered to avoid any risk of destabilising the dam. Work was carried out to address the issues and, by September of the same year, the reservoir was cleared of any further concerns.<ref name=\"ice\"/>\n\nOn 11 November 1929, the area set a new maximum daily rainfall record for Wales when {{convert|211|mm}} of rain fell, a record it retained as of 2016. As such, the site had been dubbed \"the wettest place in Wales\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/united-kingdom/galleries/britains-wettest-places/lluest-wen-reservoir-wales/ |title=Britain's Ten Wettest Places |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=16 September 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1969 flood warning===\nIn December 1969 there was a significant emergency when a local man discovered a large hole, measuring {{convert|5|ft|abbr=on}} deep and {{convert|6|ft|abbr=on}} long, after he and his horse fell into the crevice. The man alerted the emergency services who were able to free his horse and experts from the water department to inspect the dam.<ref name=\"wo\"/> The officials discovered a large crack in a pipe used to drain water from the drawoff shaft,<ref name=\"ice\"/> which led to the evacuation of 350 houses, 7 schools and the relocation of miners from [[Maerdy Colliery]].<ref name=\"wo\"/> 150 elderly residents were evacuated to higher ground and around 2,000 people also fled the valley.<ref name=\"save\"/> As the reservoir did not feature any system to drain water which are utilised in more modern structures,<ref name=\"hans\"/> in order to relieve the pressure on the damaged area, a combined effort from the army, [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF), local volunteers and the fire brigade was required to divert water away from the reservoir with the assistance of an RAF helicopter. An estimated 200\u2013300 workers were utilised in the efforts.<ref name=\"wo\"/> \n\nTo undertake repair work, the reservoir was drained by as much as {{convert|30|ft}}, leaving the site at less than a third of its usual capacity.<ref name=\"wo\"/> The workers were hampered in their efforts by the poor access to the site that delayed the arrival of heavy water pumping equipment.<ref name=\"save\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/259732582/?terms=Lluest-wen&match=1 |url-access=subscription |title=To Save a Valley |newspaper=The Guardian |last=Farrell |first=John |p=13 |date=15 January 1970 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The work cost an estimated \u00a31.5 million.<ref name=\"wo\"/> More than 450 tons of cement and 80 tons of [[bentonite]] were injected into the cores of the embankment during the repair work.<ref name=\"ice\"/> The dam was given the all clear by the end of January 1970,<ref name=\"wo\"/> although further work was carried out in the following months.<ref name=\"ice\"/> As part of the dam's new safety certificate, water was limited to 30&nbsp;ft below the top watermark, the same level that the dam had been lowered to in order to avoid bursting.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=7&docId=GALE%7CCS34042426&docType=Article&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS34042426&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Welsh dam emergency overcome |newspaper=The Times |last=Fishlock |first=Trevor |p=2 |date=26 January 1970 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\nAs part of an investigation into the incident, substantial work was carried out on the reservoir to ensure it met more modern safety standards. This included reinforcing the embankments with a 600&nbsp;mm concrete barrier and the installation of new drain-off pipework (nearly double the size of the original). The incident played a part in the introduction of the 1975 Reservoirs Act that required supervising engineers to monitor large, raised reservoirs.<ref name=\"ice\"/> The Secretary of State for Wales, [[George Thomas, 1st Viscount Tonypandy]], ordered an inspection of all reservoirs in Wales over a certain age as a result,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/259733266/?terms=Lluest-wen |url-access=subscription |title=Dams to be Inspected |newspaper=The Guardian |p=7 |date=16 January 1970 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> also declaring that \"lives have been saved\" by the emergency work carried out.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nTwo minor leaks were discovered at the end of the 20th century, although these were deemed to be of little concern regarding any serious damage to the structural integrity of the dam.<ref name=\"ice\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.geograph.org.uk/search.php?i=46200001 www.geograph.co.uk : photos of Lluest-wen Reservoir and surrounding area]\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Rhondda Cynon Taf]]\n[[Category:1898 in Wales]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1898]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Reservoir in the borough of Rhondda Cynon Taf, South Wales}}\n{{Infobox lake\n | name = Lluest-wen Reservoir\n | image = Lluest-wen Reservoir - geograph.org.uk - 1017788.jpg\n | caption = \n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Rhondda|Rhondda Fach Valley]], [[South Wales Valleys]], Wales\n | coords = {{coord|51.705|-3.525|type:waterbody_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n | type = [[reservoir]]\n | inflow = \n | outflow = \n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United Kingdom\n | length = \n | width = \n | area = \n | depth = \n | max-depth = \n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = \n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n'''Lluest-wen Reservoir''' (Welsh: ''Cronfa-ddwr Lluest-wen'') is a [[reservoir]] at the top of the [[Rhondda|Rhondda Fach Valley]] (Welsh: ''Cwm Rhondda Fach''), in the borough of [[Rhondda Cynon Taf]], South Wales. Parts of it fall within the [[Community (Wales)|communities]] of [[Rhigos]], [[Aberdare]] and [[Treherbert]]. A recreational walking route, the [[Coed Morgannwg Way]], and route 47 of the [[National Cycle Network]] run northeast and southwest of it respectively.<ref>Ordnance Survey 1:25,000 scale Explorer map sheet 166 ''Rhondda & Merthyr Tydfil/Merthyr Tudful''</ref>\n\nThe reservoir gained national attention in 1969 when significant damage was discovered that led to the evacuation of hundreds of nearby homes and prompted more than \u00a31 million of emergency repair works. \n\n==Geography and construction==\nThe reservoir was built in 1898 and covers an area of {{convert|20|acre}}.<ref name=\"wo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/40-years-rhondda-fach-nearly-1940564 |title=40 years since Rhondda Fach nearly flooded |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=21 January 2010 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> It was located at the top of the [[Rhondda Fach]], near the village of [[Maerdy]]. The site holds around {{convert|242000000|impgal}} of water.<ref name=\"wo\"/> The dam was built using earth embankments, the core of which were constructed of clay.<ref name=\"hans\">{{cite web |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1970/jan/19/wales-Lluest-wen-Reservoir |title=Wales (Lluest-Wen Reservoir) |publisher=Hansard |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ice\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.icevirtuallibrary.com/doi/full/10.1680/jdare.18.00038 |title=Lluest Wen: the near failure and subsequent repair of a Pennine type dam |journal=Dams and Reservoirs |last1=Ackers |first1=John |last2=Pether |first2=Rachel |last3=Warren |first3=Alan |pp=119\u2013122 |issue=3 |date=September 2018 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |via=Institute of Civil Engineers Virtual Library}}</ref> The banks were reinforced during the early 1970s with {{convert|600|mm|adj=on}} thick concrete.<ref name=\"ice\"/>\n\n==History==\nConstruction of the reservoir was completed in 1898. In its formative years, there were several incidents of the reservoir suffering damage. Two minor leaks in the embankments were fixed during the first decade. A larger leak was filled in with around 40 wheelbarrows of rubble in December 1910 and required refilling a year later. Settling issues caused further issues in the 1910s and rerouting work was undertaken when it was discovered that the top of the core in the embankments was only {{convert|2|ft|spell=in}} above the water level. In April 1917, a local official recommended that the reservoir be drained or the water level significantly lowered to avoid any risk of destabilising the dam. Work was carried out to address the issues and, by September of the same year, the reservoir was cleared of any further concerns.<ref name=\"ice\"/>\n\nOn 11 November 1929, the area set a new record for rainfall when {{convert|211|mm}} of rain fell within a single day, a record for a place in Wales. As such, the site had been dubbed \"the wettest place in Wales\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/united-kingdom/galleries/britains-wettest-places/lluest-wen-reservoir-wales/ |title=Britain's Ten Wettest Places |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=16 September 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1969 flood warning===\nIn December 1969 there was a significant emergency when a local man discovered a large hole, measuring {{convert|5|ft|abbr=on}} deep and {{convert|6|ft|abbr=on}} long, after he and his horse fell into the crevice. The man alerted the emergency services who were able to free his horse and experts from the water department to inspect the dam.<ref name=\"wo\"/> The officials discovered a large crack in a pipe used to drain water from the drawoff shaft,<ref name=\"ice\"/> which led to the evacuation of 350 houses, 7 schools and the relocation of miners from [[Maerdy Colliery]].<ref name=\"wo\"/> 150 elderly residents were evacuated to higher ground and around 2,000 people also fled the valley.<ref name=\"save\"/> As the reservoir did not feature any system to drain water which are utilised in more modern structures,<ref name=\"hans\"/> in order to relieve the pressure on the damaged area, a combined effort from the army, [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF), local volunteers and the fire brigade was required to divert water away from the reservoir with the assistance of an RAF helicopter. An estimated 200\u2013300 workers were utilised in the efforts.<ref name=\"wo\"/> \n\nTo undertake repair work, the reservoir was drained by as much as {{convert|30|ft}}, leaving the site at less than a third of its usual capacity.<ref name=\"wo\"/> The workers were hampered in their efforts by the poor access to the site that delayed the arrival of heavy water pumping equipment.<ref name=\"save\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/259732582/?terms=Lluest-wen&match=1 |url-access=subscription |title=To Save a Valley |newspaper=The Guardian |last=Farrell |first=John |p=13 |date=15 January 1970 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The work cost an estimated \u00a31.5 million.<ref name=\"wo\"/> More than 450 tons of cement and 80 tons of [[bentonite]] were injected into the cores of the embankment during the repair work.<ref name=\"ice\"/> The dam was given the all clear by the end of January 1970,<ref name=\"wo\"/> although further work was carried out in the following months.<ref name=\"ice\"/> As part of the dam's new safety certificate, water was limited to 30&nbsp;ft below the top watermark, the same level that the dam had been lowered to in order to avoid bursting.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=7&docId=GALE%7CCS34042426&docType=Article&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS34042426&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Welsh dam emergency overcome |newspaper=The Times |last=Fishlock |first=Trevor |p=2 |date=26 January 1970 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\nAs part of an investigation into the incident, substantial work was carried out on the reservoir to ensure it met more modern safety standards. This included reinforcing the embankments with a 600&nbsp;mm concrete barrier and the installation of new drain-off pipework (nearly double the size of the original). The incident played a part in the introduction of the 1975 Reservoirs Act that required supervising engineers to monitor large, raised reservoirs.<ref name=\"ice\"/> The Secretary of State for Wales, [[George Thomas, 1st Viscount Tonypandy]], ordered an inspection of all reservoirs in Wales over a certain age as a result,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/259733266/?terms=Lluest-wen |url-access=subscription |title=Dams to be Inspected |newspaper=The Guardian |p=7 |date=16 January 1970 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> also declaring that \"lives have been saved\" by the emergency work carried out.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nTwo minor leaks were discovered at the end of the 20th century, although these were deemed to be of little concern regarding any serious damage to the structural integrity of the dam.<ref name=\"ice\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.geograph.org.uk/search.php?i=46200001 www.geograph.co.uk : photos of Lluest-wen Reservoir and surrounding area]\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Rhondda Cynon Taf]]\n[[Category:1898 in Wales]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1898]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lluest-wen_Reservoir"}
{"title_page": "Metro Manila Film Festival Award for Best Picture", "text_new": "{{Main|Metro Manila Film Festival}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name           = [[Metro Manila Film Festival|Metro Manila Film Festival Award]] for Best Picture\n| description    = Best Picture\n| presenter      = [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority|MMDA]]\n| country        = [[Philippines]]\n| year           = 1975\n| holder         = ''[[Rainbow's Sunset]]'' ([[2018 Metro Manila Film Festival|2018]])\n| website        = {{url|http://www.mmda.gov.ph/mmff/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Metro Manila Film Festival Award for Best Picture''' is an award presented annually by the [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] (MMDA). It was first awarded at the [[1975 Metro Manila Film Festival|1st Metro Manila Film Festival]] ceremony, held in 1975; the film ''Diligin Mo ng Hamog ang Uhaw na Lupa'' starring [[Joseph Estrada]] received the award and it is given in honor of the film that \nhas delivered an outstanding creation of the film, including directing, acting, music composing, writing, editing and other efforts put forth into a film.<ref name=\"MMFF1\">[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/1975 \"Metro Manila Film Festival:1975\"]. ''IMDB''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref> The category was first named \"Best Film\" before changing it to \"Best Picture\" in 2007. Currently, nominees and winners are determined by Executive Committees, headed by the [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] Chairman and key members of the film industry.<ref>[http://www.mmda.gov.ph/mmff/ \"Official website\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005130322/http://www.mmda.gov.ph/mmff/ |date=2012-10-05 }}. ''MMDA''. Retrieved 2014-04-09.</ref>\n\n{|id=\"toc\" class=\"toc plainlinks\" style= summary=\"Metro Manila Film Festival Award for Best Picture\"\n|-\n! Contents: __NOTOC__\n|\n'''[[#1970s|1970s]]'''{{\u00b7}}'''[[#1980s|1980s]]'''{{\u00b7}}'''[[#1990s|1990s]]'''{{\u00b7}}'''[[#2000s|2000s]]'''{{\u00b7}}